@NODE "CheckGuide" "CheckGuide by Eddy Carroll"

@{par}          @{fg shine}CheckGuide 1.0 -- Checks AmigaGuide files for common errors
@{par}
@{par}             by Eddy Carroll, September 1994. Freely distributable.@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}Introduction
@{par}
@{par}If you've ever tried creating even a modestly sized AmigaGuide file by hand,
@{par}you'll have discovered that it can be quite difficult to keep track of all the
@{par}various links and cross references. As your help file gets larger, it gets
@{par}increasingly harder to ensure that you have remembered to reference all the
@{par}nodes in the file from at least one place, and haven't left any unresolved
@{par}links.
@{par}
@{par}CheckGuide is a simple utility that can detect several common errors in
@{par}AmigaGuide files. The errors it can detect are:
@{par}
@{par}· Extra plain text between an \@ENDNODE and \@NODE (AmigaGuide won't allow such
@{par}  text to ever be displayed)
@{par}
@{par}· Nodes that are defined but not referenced from any other node. Unless your
@{par}  program directly instructs AmigaGuide to access such nodes, the user won't
@{par}  easily be able to access them.
@{par}
@{par}· Links to help nodes that aren't defined within the file.
@{par}
@{par}· Open braces with no preceding \@ character (usually a simple typo).
@{par}
@{par}· \@{" Button "} constructs with no LINK command (an easy mistake to make if
@{par}  you're entering a lot of them).
@{par}
@{par}All of these options can be selectively enabled or disabled.
@{par}
@{par}        @{fg shine}CheckGuide was used in the creation of @{b}THIS@{ub} document!@{fg text}

@ENDNODE
@NODE AGIX "AGIX by Ralph Seichter"

@{par}          @{fg shine}@{u}From: AGIX.doc 1.2 (5.8.94) Copyright © Ralph Seichter@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg text}PURPOSE:
@{par}
@{par}   Although  AmigaGuide documents may have a node index, only few documents
@{par}make  use of this feature. I suppose that many people are too lazy to build
@{par}an  index  manually (I definitely am), so I thought it would be a good idea
@{par}to have this task done automatically. AGIX scans an AmigaGuide document for
@{par}references  like  \@{"foo" link "bar"} (note that AGIX does not use the node
@{par}definitions), sorts them alphabetically and produces an index file.
@{par}
@{par}   "Haven't I seen something like that before?" you might ask. Well, I have
@{par}seen  one  similar  program  so far, but on my machine it didn't work, so I
@{par}decided  to  try  it myself. The result is short (only 1960 bytes) and uses
@{par}StrnCmp() from locale.library instead of stricmp(), if available, and has a
@{par}very nice sounding name. :)

@ENDNODE
@NODE NewEdit "NewEdit by Uwe Röhm & Paul Huxham"

@{par}NewEdit                                                             NewEdit
@{par}
@{par}   PURPOSE
@{par} To provide aditional functions and operators during string gadget
@{par} editing.
@{par}
@{par}   COPYRIGHT
@{par} The copyright in this package is owned by Paul Huxham © 1995.
@{par} NewEdit 1.9 is based on the original NewEdit by Uwe Röhm.
@{par}
@{par}   DISTRIBUTION
@{par} NewEdit should be distributed at no charge to the end user however
@{par} should a duplication charge be made, it should not exceed the cost of a
@{par} blank 3.5" disk. The NewEdit executable and documentation is public
@{par} domain and no payment is required for its use.
@{par} For commercial applications of NewEdit, contact the author for
@{par} further information concerning distribution.
@{par}
@{par}   CONTENTS
@{par} This package should contain:
@{par} NewEdit - The main program.
@{par} NewEdit.info - The main programs icon.
@{par} NewEdit.doc - The document you are reading now.
@{par}
@{par}   USAGE
@{par} The following key commands are standard functions provided by OS 2.0:
@{par}   CURSOR LEFT         cursor to previous character
@{par}   SHIFT CURSOR LEFT   cursor to start of line
@{par}   CURSOR RIGHT        cursor to next character
@{par}   SHIFT CURSOR RIGHT  cursor to end of line
@{par}   DEL                 delete the character under the cursor
@{par}   SHIFT DEL           delete from the character under the cursor to EOL
@{par}   BACKSPACE           delete the character to the left of the cursor
@{par}   SHIFT BACKSPACE     delete from the character to the left of the cursor
@{par}                       to the start of the line
@{par}   RETURN or ENTER     terminate input and deactivate the gadget
@{par}   RAMIGA Q            restore gadgets contents before alteration
@{par}   RAMIGA X            clear the string gadget
@{par}
@{par} The following key commands are provided by NewEdit 1.9:
@{par}   ALT CURSOR RIGHT    next word
@{par}   ALT CURSOR LEFT     previous word
@{par}   ALT BACKSPACE       delete previous word
@{par}   ALT DEL             delete next word
@{par}   RALT CURSOR UP      go to prev gadget (accepting contents)
@{par}   RALT CURSOR DOWN    go to next gadget (accepting contents)
@{par}   ESC                 leave gadget (accepting contents)
@{par}   RALT C or RAMIGA C  copy gadget contents to clipboard
@{par}   RALT V or RAMIGA V  paste contents of clipboard to gadget
@{par}   RALT I or RAMIGA I  increments a numbered filename by one
@{par}   RALT RSHIFT I or
@{par}   RAMIGA RSHIFT I     decrements a numbered filename by one
@{par}   RALT G or RAMIGA G  toggle the case of indicated character
@{par}   SHIFT RALT G or
@{par}   SHIFT RAMIGA G      toggle the case of characters until EOL or
@{par}                       non alphabetic character is found
@{par}   RALT D or RAMIGA D  Insert the current date
@{par}
@{par} The reason for RALT as well as RAMIGA is that some applications eg ASL
@{par} file requester trap and use the RAMIGA key for other functions. By
@{par} using the RALT key you can still access the functions.
@{par}
@{par} The following parameters can be set either as tooltypes or via command
@{par} line switches when running NewEdit:
@{par}  RALT - If you do not wish to have the RALT functions available (those
@{par}         key commands that can use either RALT or RAMIGA, use this
@{par}         parameter to disable the RALT keys. (Keys like RALT CURSOR LEFT
@{par}         will still work).
@{par}
@{par}  CLIPUNIT - Sets the clipboard unit used to copy to and from.
@{par}
@{par}   COMPLIER
@{par} NewEdit was written and compiled using CED V3.5 and SAS/C 6.55 on
@{par} an Amiga 4000/040. It should perform equally well on a 68000.
@{par} Enforcer was used to detect and correct programming errors.
@{par}
@{par}   BUGS
@{par} The only thing I can find is that in the first string gadget activated
@{par} after NewEdit is installed, the cursor will jump to the right hand end
@{par} of the gadget. I don't know why this happens. This also happened in Uwes
@{par} original version. I don't process any events other than key events so I
@{par} can't see how a mouse click is causing this to happen.
@{par}
@{par} Should you find any bugs, please report them so that they can be fixed.
@{par} Likewise any suggestions for improvment of should be forwarded so that
@{par} they can be addressed.
@{par}
@{par}   HISTORY
@{par} 1.8b Initial release.
@{par} 1.9  Removed locale code and error messages (like: You need KS 2.0).
@{par}      General code cleanup and enhancments.
@{par}      Added paste date.
@{par}      Added decrement a file number.
@{par}      New document format for the instructions.
@{par}
@{par}   THANKYOU
@{par}  Uwe Röhm - For the original version that I have enhanced (butchered??).
@{par}  Steve Quartly - Numerous ideas and long nights playing Deluxe Galaga.
@{par}
@{par}   AUTHOR
@{par} You can contact the author via:
@{par}   Email: paulh@Perth.DIALix.oz.au
@{par} or
@{par}   P.O. Box 875
@{par}   Morley,
@{par}   Perth,
@{par}   Western Australia 6943

@ENDNODE
@NODE Installation "DOpusFuncs - Installation"

@{par}See also: @{" Usage " LINK Usage}
@{par}          @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" Debug Version " LINK DebugVersion}
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} This is just a @{u}suggestion@{uu} of how to install it. You can do with it
@{par}      what you want.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Make sure the @{fg fill}"P"@{fg text} bit is set as this program is @{fg shine}'Pure'@{fg text} and may be made
@{par}  @{b}resident@{ub} @{fg fill}(see below)@{fg text}.
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Protect DOpusFuncs +P @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Copy the main file to @{fg fill}DOpus5:c/@{fg text}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Copy DOpusFuncs DOpus5:c/ @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Copy the AmigaGuide to @{fg fill}DOpus5:Help/@{fg text}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Copy DOpusFuncs.guide DOpus5:Help/ @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Read the @{" usage " LINK Usage} and @{" examples " LINK Examples} sections and set up whatever buttons you
@{par}  like.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} If you want to make the command @{b}resident@{ub} (to save loading time), add this
@{par}  line to your @{fg fill}S:User-Startup@{fg text}...
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Resident DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs @{bg back}
@{par}  ...and change all commands to reference @{fg fill}"DOpusFuncs"@{fg text} instead of
@{par}  @{fg fill}"DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs"@{fg text}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage "DOpusFuncs - Usage"

@{par}See also: @{" Installation " LINK Installation}
@{par}          @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}DOpusFuncs@{fg text} command takes the following command-line parameters:
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}Mandatory:@{fg text}
@{par} @{" RexxPort     " LINK U_RexxPort}  Specify the @{fg fill}ARexx port@{fg text} to talk with.
@{par}@{fg shine}Action selection:@{fg text}
@{par} @{" ClipEntry    " LINK U_ClipEntry}  @{b}Copy@{ub} @{fg fill}name@{fg text} of @{b}selected entries@{ub} (etc.) -> @{fg fill}clipboard@{fg text}.
@{par} @{" DirToDest    " LINK U_DirToDest}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} @{fg fill}'Source'@{fg text}-@{b}selected dir@{ub} -> @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister.
@{par} @{" ParentToDest " LINK U_ParentToDest}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} @{fg fill}'Source'@{fg text}-@{b}parent dir@{ub} -> @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister.
@{par} @{" WinCopy      " LINK U_WinCopy}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} @{b}Copy@{ub} @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister -> @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister.
@{par} @{" WinSwap      " LINK U_WinSwap}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} @{b}Swap@{ub} @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} and @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} listers.
@{par}@{fg shine}Lister control:@{fg text}
@{par} @{" NewDest      " LINK U_NewDest}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Open a @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister before <@{bg fill}action@{bg back}>.
@{par} @{" DestDir      " LINK U_DestDir}  Specify the new @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister's @{b}path@{ub}.
@{par} @{" DestPos      " LINK U_DestPos}  Specify the new @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister's @{b}dimensions@{ub}.
@{par} @{" DestLock     " LINK U_DestLock}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Make the new lister '@{b}locked@{ub}-dest'.
@{par}
@{par} @{" NewSource    " LINK U_NewSource}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Open a @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister before <@{bg fill}action@{bg back}>.
@{par} @{" SourceDir    " LINK U_SourceDir}  Specify the new @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister's @{b}path@{ub}.
@{par} @{" SourcePos    " LINK U_SourcePos}  Specify the new @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister's @{b}dimensions@{ub}.
@{par} @{" SourceLock   " LINK U_SourceLock}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Make the new lister '@{b}locked@{ub}-source'.
@{par}
@{par} @{" NoFront      " LINK U_NoFront}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} @{b}Don't@{ub} bring the @{b}screen to front@{ub} for new listers.
@{par} @{" NoNew        " LINK U_NoNew}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Disable automatic openning of new listers.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}ReadArgs() Template:@{uu}@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}RP=REXXPORT/A, CLIPENTRY/K/M, DIRTODEST/S, PARENTTODEST/S, WINCOPY/S,
WINSWAP/S, NEWSOURCE/S, SOURCEDIR/K, SOURCEPOS/K, SOURCELOCK/S,
NEW=NEWDEST/S, DIR=DESTDIR/K, POS=DESTPOS/K, LOCK=DESTLOCK/S, NOFRONT/S,
NONEW/S

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_RexxPort "DOpusFuncs - Usage, RexxPort"

@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}
@{par}Alias: @{fg fill}"RP"@{fg text}
@{par}
@REMARK
@REMARK The "@{fg fill} <text> @{fg fill}" is required due to an AmigaGuide bug.
@REMARK
@{par}@{fg fill}RexxPort@{fg text} is a @{b}mandatory keyword@{ub} with which you specify the name of @{fg fill}DOpus5's
ARexx @{fg fill}port@{fg text}. This should @{b}always@{ub} be done using the @{fg shine}{Qp}@{fg text} function within
the @{fg fill}DOpus5 command-editor@{fg text}, as shown in all of the @{" examples " LINK Examples}.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Port names are @{u}case-sensitive@{uu}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_ClipEntry "DOpusFuncs - Usage, ClipEntry"
@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" DirToDest " LINK U_DirToDest}
@{par}          @{" ParentToDest " LINK U_ParentToDest}
@{par}          @{" WinCopy " LINK U_WinCopy}
@{par}          @{" WinSwap " LINK U_WinSwap}
@{par}>>>>>>>>> @{" Known Bugs " LINK Future}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}ClipEntry@{fg text} @{b}keyword@{ub} takes @{b}all@{ub} words from the command-line which are not
part of other arguments and puts them in the @{fg fill}clipboard@{fg text} as @{b}one@{ub} string. When
used on a @{fg fill}DOpus5 button@{fg text} with the @{fg shine}{}@{fg text} commands you can do useful things such
as @{b}copy@{ub} the @{b}names@{ub} of @{b}all selected files@{ub} to the @{fg fill}clipboard@{fg text}.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}Quotes@{fg text} will be placed around any sub-strings with @{b}spaces@{ub} in, provided you
have left the @{fg fill}"No file quote"@{fg text} switch @{b}off@{ub}.
@{par}
@{par}Have a look at the @{" examples " LINK Examples} section to see some of the things it can
do.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_DirToDest "DOpusFuncs - Usage, DirToDest"

@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" ClipEntry " LINK U_ClipEntry}
@{par}          @{" ParentToDest " LINK U_ParentToDest}
@{par}          @{" WinCopy " LINK U_WinCopy}
@{par}          @{" WinSwap " LINK U_WinSwap}
@{par}          @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource}
@{par}          @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest}
@{par}          @{" NoNew " LINK U_NoNew}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}DirToDest@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} causes whatever @{b}directory@{ub} is @{b}selected@{ub} in the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} 
lister to be read into the @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister. Currently, under @{fg fill}DOpus 5.11@{fg text}, the
only way to do this is to @{fg shine}drag'n'drop@{fg text} the directory while holding down the
@{fg shine}shift-key@{fg text}, @{i}and believe me, it's a pain in the arse. @{ui}@{bg shine}:-/@{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}By default, if there isn't a @{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister, a @{b}new@{ub} lister will be
openned for you. You can turn this off with the @{" NoNew " LINK U_NoNew} @{b}switch@{ub}, while you
can @{b}force@{ub} a @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister to be openned (even if there already
is one) with the @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest} @{b}switch@{ub}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_ParentToDest "DOpusFuncs - Usage, ParentToDest"

@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" ClipEntry " LINK U_ClipEntry}
@{par}          @{" DirToDest " LINK U_DirToDest}
@{par}          @{" WinCopy " LINK U_WinCopy}
@{par}          @{" WinSwap " LINK U_WinSwap}
@{par}          @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource}
@{par}          @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest}
@{par}          @{" NoNew " LINK U_NoNew}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}ParentToDest@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} causes the @{b}parent directory@{ub} of the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister
to be read into the @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister is at the @{fg shine}root of a volume, @{fg fill}ParentToDest@{fg text} will
@{par}      cause a @{fg shine}DeviceList@{fg text} to appear in the @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister.
@{par}
@{par}By default, if there isn't a @{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister, a @{b}new@{ub} lister will be
openned for you. You can turn this off with the @{" NoNew " LINK U_NoNew} @{b}switch@{ub}, while you
can @{b}force@{ub} a @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister to be openned (even if there already
is one) with the @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest} @{b}switch@{ub}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_WinCopy "DOpusFuncs - Usage, WinCopy"

@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" ClipEntry " LINK U_ClipEntry}
@{par}          @{" DirToDest " LINK U_DirToDest}
@{par}          @{" ParentToDest " LINK U_ParentToDest}
@{par}          @{" WinSwap " LINK U_WinSwap}
@{par}          @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource}
@{par}          @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest}
@{par}          @{" NoNew " LINK U_NoNew}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}WinCopy@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} causes the @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister to read in the same path as the
@{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister. That is, it @{b}copies@{ub} the contents of the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister to
the @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} one, like the old command which was built-into @{fg fill}DOpus4@{fg text}.
@{par}
@{par}By default, if there isn't a @{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister, a @{b}new@{ub} lister will be
openned for you. You can turn this off with the @{" NoNew " LINK U_NoNew} @{b}switch@{ub}, while you
can @{b}force@{ub} a @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister to be openned (even if there already
is one) with the @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest} @{b}switch@{ub}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_WinSwap "DOpusFuncs - Usage, WinSwap"

@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" ClipEntry " LINK U_ClipEntry}
@{par}          @{" DirToDest " LINK U_DirToDest}
@{par}          @{" ParentToDest " LINK U_ParentToDest}
@{par}          @{" WinCopy " LINK U_WinCopy}
@{par}          @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource}
@{par}          @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}WinSwap@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} causes the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} and @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} listers to @{b}swap@{ub} around.
In other words, the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister displays the path previously in the
@{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister, and vice versa, like the old command which was built-into
@{fg fill}DOpus4@{fg text}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_NewDest "DOpusFuncs - Usage, NewDest"

@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" DestDir " LINK U_DestDir}
@{par}          @{" DestPos " LINK U_DestPos}
@{par}          @{" DestLock " LINK U_DestLock}
@{par}          @{" NoFront " LINK U_NoFront}
@{par}          @{" DirToDest " LINK U_DirToDest}
@{par}          @{" ParentToDest " LINK U_ParentToDest}
@{par}          @{" WinCopy " LINK U_WinCopy}
@{par}          @{" WinSwap " LINK U_WinSwap}
@{par}          @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource}
@{par}
@{par}Alias: @{fg fill}"New"@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}NewDest@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} causes a @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister to be openned before
whatever selected @{bg fill}action@{bg back}, if any, takes place.
@{par}
@{par}When used in combination with the @{bg fill}action@{bg back}@{fg fill}-selection @{b}switches@{ub}@{fg text}, @{fg fill}NewDest@{fg text} can
do useful things such as open a @{b}new@{ub} lister and then read the @{b}parent@{ub} of
the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister into it, without altering the @{i}original @{ui}@{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister.
@{par}
@{par}There are a couple of @{" examples " LINK Examples} of ways in which you can use this @{b}switch@{ub},
although I'm not going to list @{i}all @{ui}of them.
@{par}
@{par}Certain attributes of the @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister can be defined by
using the @{" DestDir " LINK U_DestDir}, @{" DestPos " LINK U_DestPos}, and @{" DestLock " LINK U_DestLock} @{b}keywords@{ub} and @{b}switch@{ub}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_DestDir "DOpusFuncs - Usage, DestDir"

@{par}See also: @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest}
@{par}          @{" DestPos " LINK U_DestPos}
@{par}          @{" DestLock " LINK U_DestLock}
@{par}          @{" SourceDir " LINK U_SourceDir}
@{par}          @{" SourcePos " LINK U_SourcePos}
@{par}          @{" SourceLock " LINK U_SourceLock}
@{par}
@{par}Alias: @{fg fill}"Dir"@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}DestDir@{fg text} @{b}keyword@{ub} lets you define what @{b}path@{ub} the @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister,
created with the @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest} @{b}switch@{ub}, will take. The @{b}keyword@{ub} is @{b}optional@{ub},
and if you don't give it, the @{b}new@{ub} lister will have an @{b}empty path@{ub} which
@{i}may @{ui}result in a @{fg shine}DeviceList@{fg text}, depending on your @{fg fill}DOpus5 environment@{fg text}.
@{par}
@{par}The only real use I can see for this @{b}keyword@{ub} is for openning a @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} 
lister pointing to a @{b}path@{ub} you want to use and then @{" WinSwapping " LINK U_WinSwap} so
that your @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister reads the @{b}new@{ub} path and the previous contents of
the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister are put aside.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_DestPos "DOpusFuncs - Usage, DestPos"

@{par}See also: @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest}
@{par}          @{" DestDir " LINK U_DestDir}
@{par}          @{" DestLock " LINK U_DestLock}
@{par}          @{" SourceDir " LINK U_SourceDir}
@{par}          @{" SourcePos " LINK U_SourcePos}
@{par}          @{" SourceLock " LINK U_SourceLock}
@{par}
@{par}Alias: @{fg fill}"Pos"@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}By default, new listers created with the @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest} command open under
your mouse-pointer with either the size you set in your @{fg fill}environment @{fg text}file
(DOpus 5.11 and above only), or the size defined by the path's @{fg fill}icon@{fg text}, if it
has one. The @{fg fill}DestPos@{fg text} @{b}keyword@{ub} can be used to set a different size and
position for the lister.
@{par}
@{par}The format is @{fg fill}<x-pos>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<y-pos>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<width>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<height>@{fg text}, e.g. 50/10/100/200
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE: @{ub}Specifying 0/0/@{fg fill}<w>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<h>@{fg text} will make the lister open under the mouse in
@{par}      the current version of @{fg fill}Directory Opus@{fg text} (5.11). This means that it is
@{par}      not possible to open a lister in the top corner of the screen. @{bg shine}:-(@{bg back}

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_DestLock "DOpusFuncs - Usage, DestLock"

@{par}See also: @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest}
@{par}          @{" DestDir " LINK U_DestDir}
@{par}          @{" DestPos " LINK U_DestPos}
@{par}          @{" SourceDir " LINK U_SourceDir}
@{par}          @{" SourcePos " LINK U_SourcePos}
@{par}          @{" SourceLock " LINK U_SourceLock}
@{par}
@{par}Alias: @{fg fill}"Lock"@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}DestLock@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} causes @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} listers openned with the @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest} 
@{b}switch@{ub} to open in @{fg fill}'locked-dest'@{fg text} mode.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_NewSource "DOpusFuncs - Usage, NewSource"

@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" SourceDir " LINK U_SourceDir}
@{par}          @{" SourcePos " LINK U_SourcePos}
@{par}          @{" SourceLock " LINK U_SourceLock}
@{par}          @{" NoFront " LINK U_NoFront}
@{par}          @{" DirToDest " LINK U_DirToDest}
@{par}          @{" ParentToDest " LINK U_ParentToDest}
@{par}          @{" WinCopy " LINK U_WinCopy}
@{par}          @{" WinSwap " LINK U_WinSwap}
@{par}          @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}NewSource@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} causes a @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister to be openned before
whatever selected @{bg fill}action@{bg back}, if any, takes place.
@{par}
@{par}Certain attributes of the @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister can be defined by
using the @{" SourceDir " LINK U_SourceDir}, @{" SourcePos " LINK U_SourcePos}, and @{" SourceLock " LINK U_SourceLock} @{b}keywords@{ub} and @{b}switch@{ub}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_SourceDir "DOpusFuncs - Usage, SourceDir"

@{par}See also: @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource}
@{par}          @{" SourcePos " LINK U_SourcePos}
@{par}          @{" SourceLock " LINK U_SourceLock}
@{par}          @{" DestDir " LINK U_DestDir}
@{par}          @{" DestPos " LINK U_DestPos}
@{par}          @{" DestLock " LINK U_DestLock}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}SourceDir@{fg text} @{b}keyword@{ub} lets you define what @{b}path@{ub} the @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister,
created with the @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource} @{b}switch@{ub}, will take. The @{b}keyword@{ub} is @{b}optional@{ub},
and if you don't give it, the @{b}new@{ub} lister will have an @{b}empty path@{ub} which
@{i}may @{ui}result in a @{fg shine}DeviceList@{fg text}, depending on your @{fg fill}DOpus5 environment@{fg text}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_SourcePos "DOpusFuncs - Usage, SourcePos"

@{par}See also: @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource}
@{par}          @{" SourceDir " LINK U_SourceDir}
@{par}          @{" SourceLock " LINK U_SourceLock}
@{par}          @{" DestDir " LINK U_DestDir}
@{par}          @{" DestPos " LINK U_DestPos}
@{par}          @{" DestLock " LINK U_DestLock}
@{par}
@{par}By default, new listers created with the @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewDest} command open under
your mouse-pointer with either the size you set in your @{fg fill}environment @{fg text}file
(DOpus 5.11 and above only), or the size defined by the path's @{fg fill}icon@{fg text}, if it
has one. The @{fg fill}SourcePos@{fg text} @{b}keyword@{ub} can be used to set a different size and
position for the lister.
@{par}
@{par}The format is @{fg fill}<x-pos>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<y-pos>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<width>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<height>@{fg text}, e.g. 50/10/100/200
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE: @{ub}Specifying 0/0/@{fg fill}<w>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<h>@{fg text} will make the lister open under the mouse in
@{par}      the current version of @{fg fill}Directory Opus@{fg text} (5.11). This means that it is
@{par}      not possible to open a lister in the top corner of the screen. @{bg shine}:-(@{bg back}

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_SourceLock "DOpusFuncs - Usage, SourceLock"

@{par}See also: @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource}
@{par}          @{" SourceDir " LINK U_SourceDir}
@{par}          @{" SourcePos " LINK U_SourcePos}
@{par}          @{" DestDir " LINK U_DestDir}
@{par}          @{" DestPos " LINK U_DestPos}
@{par}          @{" DestLock " LINK U_DestLock}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}SourceLock@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} causes @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} listers openned with the
@{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource} @{b}switch@{ub} to open in @{fg fill}'locked-source'@{fg text} mode.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_NoFront "DOpusFuncs - Usage, NoFront"

@{par}See also: @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest}
@{par}          @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource}
@{par}
@{par}By default, when @{" NewDest " LINK U_NewDest} and @{" NewSource " LINK U_NewSource} open a @{b}new@{ub} lister the @{fg fill}DOpus
screen@{fg text} will be popped to the @{b}front@{ub} as you probably want to see and use your
newly created lister. If you specify the @{fg fill}NoFront@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} on the command-line
the screens are left alone.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_NoNew "DOpusFuncs - Usage, NoNew"

@{par}See also: @{" DirToDest " LINK U_DirToDest}
@{par}          @{" ParentToDest " LINK U_ParentToDest}
@{par}          @{" WinCopy " LINK U_WinCopy}
@{par}
@{par}By default, when @{" DirToDest " LINK U_DirToDest}, @{" ParentToDest " LINK U_ParentToDest}, or @{" WinCopy " LINK U_WinCopy}, looks for a
@{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister and one doesn't exist, a @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister
is @{i}automatically openned.@{ui} This behaviour is similar to the internal
@{fg fill}DOpus@{fg text} commands and can be very useful - however, there may be times when
it isn't desireable. If you use the @{fg fill}NoNew@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} you'll get an @{fg fill}error-
requester@{fg text} instead of a new lister.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Examples "DOpusFuncs - Examples"

@{par}See also: @{" Usage " LINK Usage}
@{par}
@{par}Here are some quick examples of how to use the program:
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} For a button which @{b}swaps@{ub} the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} and @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} listers:
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} AmigaDOS @{bg back}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs {Qp} WinSwap @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} For a button which @{b}copies@{ub} the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister to the @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} one:
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} AmigaDOS @{bg back}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs {Qp} WinCopy @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} For a button which opens a @{b}clone@{ub} of the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister:
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} AmigaDOS @{bg back}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs {Qp} WinCopy NewDest @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} For a button which reads the @{b}directory selected@{ub} in the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister
@{par}  into the @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister:
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} AmigaDOS @{bg back}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs {Qp} DirToDest @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} For a button which reads the @{b}parent@{ub} of the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister into a new
@{par}  lister:
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} AmigaDOS @{bg back}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs {Qp} ParentToDest NewDest @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} For a button which @{b}copies@{ub} the @{b}names@{ub} of @{b}all selected entries@{ub} in the
@{par}  @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister to the @{fg fill}clipboard@{fg text}:
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} AmigaDOS @{bg back}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs {Qp} ClipEntry {O} @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} For a button which does the @{i}same as above @{ui}but includes the @{b}full path@{ub} of
@{par}  all the files:
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} AmigaDOS @{bg back}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs {Qp} ClipEntry {F} @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} For a button which @{b}copies@{ub} the @{b}name@{ub} of the @{b}first selected entry@{ub}:
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} AmigaDOS @{bg back}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs {Qp} ClipEntry {o} @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}-@{fg text} If you put one of the three examples above in one of the @{b}left-
@{par}  mousebutton@{ub} functions of a @{b}button bank@{ub} you are able to @{fg shine}drag@{fg text} files and
@{par}  icons from listers and @{fg shine}drop@{fg text} them on the button to have their names put
@{par}  in the clipboard (@{i}of course, @{ui}you can still select-n-click, too).
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} For a button which @{b}copies@{ub} the @{b}path@{ub} of the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister to the
@{par}  @{fg fill}clipboard@{fg text}:
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} AmigaDOS @{bg back}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} DOpus5:c/DOpusFuncs {Qp} ClipEntry {s} @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}- @{fg text}I hope you get the idea!? @{fg text}Obviously there are many other combinations.
@{par}

@ENDNODE
@NODE DebugVersion "DOpusFuncs - Debug Version"

@{par}As well as the main @{fg fill}"DOpusFuncs"@{fg text} executable file, you should also find a
file called @{fg fill}"DOpusFuncs_DEBUG"@{fg text}. The two programs are identical apart from:
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} The @{b}debug@{ub} version contains all the @{fg fill}debug labels@{fg text} and @{fg fill}headers@{fg text}.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} The @{b}debug@{ub} version outputs some extra information while it is running.
@{par}  (Most of the time it just reports the commands sent to the @{fg fill}DOpus ARexx
@{par}  port @{fg text}and what the results are).
@{par}
@{par}If you have any problems getting things to work, you should try running
the @{b}debug@{ub} version and see if you can see what's going on. If there appears
to be a @{b}bug@{ub} in the program, @{" reporting " LINK Credits} what the @{b}debug@{ub} version outputs could
help me a great deal in working out what is going wrong.

@ENDNODE
@NODE History "DOpusFuncs - History"

@{par}See also: @{" Future " LINK Future}
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Versions numbering is in the @{fg shine}<version>@{fg fill}.@{fg shine}<revision>@{fg text} format. This means
@{par}      that version @{fg shine}1.10 @{fg text}(one.ten) is @{b}newer@{ub} than version @{fg shine}1.2 @{fg text}(one.two).
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.1 (Private release) - 19-Aug-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}First@{ub} release for testing.
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.2 (Private release) - 21-Aug-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} W@{fg fill}r@{fg shine}o@{fg fill}t@{fg text}e @{bg fill}t@{bg shine}h@{bg fill}i@{bg shine}s@{bg back} @{b}A@{ub}@{u}m@{uu}@{b}i@{ub}@{u}g@{uu}@{b}a@{ub}@{u}G@{uu}@{b}u@{ub}@{u}i@{uu}@{b}d@{ub}@{u}e@{uu}.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Fixed@{ub} something in the way that @{fg fill}ARexx@{fg text} messages are sent to @{fg fill}DOpus5@{fg text}.
@{par}  (This shouldn't have caused any problems, but it is done properly now).
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Removed@{ub} the @{fg fill}NoReq@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} because it was of very little use.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Changed@{ub} the @{fg shine}DeviceList@{fg text} routine to wait for the lister to finish the
@{par}  @{fg shine}DevieList@{fg text} before restoring the orginal @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister. Previously this
@{par}  could happen too quickly and cause the @{fg shine}DeviceList@{fg text} to appear in the
@{par}  wrong lister.
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.3 (Private release) - 27-Aug-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} my @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}email address@{fg text} to the @{" credits " LINK Credits} node.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} new @{" ClipEntry " LINK U_ClipEntry} @{b}switch@{ub} for the @{fg shine}new function@{fg text}. (@{" Thanks Trevor! " LINK Credits})
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} an @{fg fill}icon@{fg text} for this 'guide. (@{" Thanks Trevor! " LINK Credits})
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Fixed@{ub} alphabetical-sorting in the @{" credits " LINK Credits} node. (@{" Thanks Trevor! " LINK Credits})
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Fixed@{ub} an extra comma (,) in the ReadArgs() template.
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.4 (MWB_DOpus_7.lha release) - 10-Sep-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Changed@{ub} @{" ClipEntry " LINK U_ClipEntry}. (Too detailed to list here).
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{i}Where useful, @{ui}new listers will open @{b}automatically@{ub} if there isn't a lister
@{par}  of the required type open already (just like @{fg fill}DOpus5's@{fg text} internal commands).
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} @{" NoNew " LINK U_NoNew} @{b}switch@{ub} to disable the above feature.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Fixed@{ub} some error requesters which were using @{fg fill}EasyRequestArgs()@{fg text} instead
@{par}  of @{fg fill}"dopus request"@{fg text}.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} two new @{" known bugs " LINK Future}, neither of which are my fault. :)
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Fixed@{ub} a few node titles which had @{fg fill}"CDOpus"@{fg text} in them.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Updated@{ub} the @{" NewEdit " LINK NewEdit} node.

@Remark VERSION NUMBERS/DATES: VER string and Contents Node.
@Remark WHEN ADDING NEW NODES, DON'T FORGET TO UPDATE THE INDEX.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Future "DOpusFuncs - Future & Known Bugs"

@{par}See also: @{" History " LINK History}
@{par}          @{" Credits " LINK Credits}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u} To Do: @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Turn it into a propper @{fg shine}DOpus5 module@{fg text}, turning everything into @{b}internal@{ub} 
@{par}  @{fg fill}'Commands'@{fg text}. (If I can @{b}bribe@{ub} @{fg fill}Jon@{fg text} enough to let me in on the secret!)
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Add the ability to @{fg fill}clone@{fg text} @{b}multiple@{ub} source listers. (Does anyone actually
@{par}  want this? I won't add it if noone asks as it would be a pain to do).
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} If you want something, @{" ask " LINK Credits} for it!
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u} Known Bugs: @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Two @{fg fill}Enforcer hits@{fg text} have been @{" reported " LINK Credits} in @{fg shine}RexxSend@{fg text} which shares many of
@{par}  its routines with this program.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Due to what appears to be a problem in the @{fg fill}"lister copy"@{fg text} command, listers
@{par}  which have been @{b}copied@{ub} or @{b}swapped@{ub} @{i}may @{ui}revert back to their previous paths
@{par}  when @{b}iconified@{ub}.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Under @{fg fill}Directory Opus 5.11@{fg text} it is not possible to open new listers in the
@{par}  top-right corner, because the coordinates @{fg shine}0/0@{fg text} make the lister open under
@{par}  the mouse pointer.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} There is a bug in the @{fg fill}OS3.1 AmigaGuide@{fg text} which can cause extra spaces,
@{par}  missing spaces, and duplicated words at @{fg fill}line-wraps@{fg text}. @{b}This it not my fault!@{ub}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} The @{fg fill}OS3.1 Autodocs@{fg text} state that there are some @{b}bugs@{ub} in the @{fg fill}OS2 version@{fg text} of
@{par}  @{fg fill}iffparse.library@{fg text}. If @{" ClipEntry " LINK U_ClipEntry} appears to go bananas and you're using
@{par}  @{fg fill}OS2@{fg text}, it @{i}might @{ui}not be my fault. @{bg shine}:-)@{bg back}

@ENDNODE
